  "explanation_used": "1. **Opening statement**: This neuron strongly responds to **news-style text segments containing datelines, timestamps, or explicit source attributions** (such as \"ISLAMABAD (Dunya News) \u2013\", \"08:40 PM ISLAMABAD, (UrduPoint...\", or \"By David M. Greenwald Executive Editor San Francisco, CA \u2013\").\n\n2. **Domain coverage**: The pattern appears in multilingual news reporting (English, Spanish, Arabic, Indonesian, etc.) across diverse topics\u2014geopolitics, crime, health, sports, and business. It specifically activates on text that opens with location/time stamps (\"ISLAMABAD, May 22 (APP):\"), attribution phrases (\"According to The Blaze,\"), or journalistic bylines/credit lines, often at the beginning of a report or segment.\n\n3. **Contrast with low-activation examples**: The high-activation texts consistently begin with journalistic metadata (location, source, time, or author credit), while low-activation examples either lack this framing entirely, are generic narrative sentences, or are incomplete fragments without explicit news-source scaffolding.\n\n4. **Closing interpretation**: The neuron detects the structural framing of news articles and dispatches rather than their specific content. It acts as a \"news-format identifier\" by firing on textual markers that signal a report is originating from a news organization or wire service.",
